se nations and territories over which England claimed dominion. In so doing, the collection offers important new insights into political and social developments at times of major turmoil, including Edward I's war with Scotland, the deposition of Edward II, and the Peasants' Revolt of 1381, while also exploring the mechanisms used to ensure peace and the smooth-running of a kingdom during a time of immense change. DAVID GREEN is Lecturer in British Studies and History, Harlaxton College; CHRIS GIVEN-WILSON is Professor of Late Medieval History, University of St Andrews. Contributors: James Bothwell, S.W. Dempsey, Matthew Hefferan, Samuel Lane, Cary J. Nederman, W. Mark Ormrod, Bridget Wells-Furby  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArchbishop Winchelsea.  aEdward I.  aEdward II.  aEdward III.  aEngland.  aFourteenth-Century.  aLeicester.  aMagna Carta.  aOrdinances of 1311.  aPeasants' Revolt of 1381.  aPlugenet family.  aRichard II.  agenealogy.  ahouse.  amedieval bishops.  apolitical history.  aroyal household.1 aBothwell, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDempsey, S. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiven-Wilson, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGreen, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHefferan, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLane, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNederman, Cary J, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNederman, Cary J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrmrod, W Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc